HEADWORD: Thresh
<hw>Thresh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>
}</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thrashed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thrashing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>⟦thorn⟧reschen</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧reshen</ets>, to beat, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧erscan</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧rescan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>dorschen</ets>, OD.
<ets>derschen</ets>, G. <ets>dreschen</ets>, OHG. <ets>dreskan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧reskja</ets>, Sw. <ets>tr⟦oum⟧ska</ets>, Dan.
<ets>t⟦ae⟧rske</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧riskan</ets>, Lith.
<ets>traszketi</ets> to rattle, Russ. <ets>treskate</ets> to burst,
crackle, <ets>tresk'</ets> a crash, OSlav. <ets>troska</ets> a stroke of
lighting. Cf. <er>Thresh</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To beat out grain
from, as straw or husks; to beat the straw or husk of (grain) with a
flail; to beat off, as the kernels of grain; <as>as, to <ex>thrash</ex>
wheat, rye, or oats; to <ex>thrash</ex> over the old
straw</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wheat was reaped, <qex>thrashed</qex>, and winnowed by
machines.</q> <rj><qau>H. Spencer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beat soundly, as with a stick or whip; to
drub.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thresh</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Thrash</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thresh
<hw>Thresh</hw>}</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To practice thrashing grain or the like; to perform the
business of beating grain from straw; <as>as, a man who
<ex>thrashes</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to labor; to toil; also, to move
violently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I rather would be Maevius, <qex>thrash</qex> for rhymes,⟦br⟧
Like his, the scorn and scandal of the times.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thrashel</ent>⟦br⟧

